Thatâ€™s the same as your browser saying â€œâš ï¸ Your connection is not private.â€

Because the CA that signed it isnâ€™t part of any trusted CA list that AWS or browsers or systems recognize.

ğŸ” Step 4: Security problem â€” CA private key inside Kubernetes

When cert-manager is the CA, it stores the private key (the signing key) in a Kubernetes Secret:

kubectl get secret my-root-ca -o yaml


That means if anyone gets access to your cluster â€” even read-only access to Secrets â€” they can:

Extract that key

Use it to sign their own fake certificates

Pretend to be any service in your cluster

Thatâ€™s a huge risk in production, because the whole â€œtrustâ€ of your TLS system can be forged.

ğŸ¢ Step 5: What AWS PCA fixes

AWS PCA fixes both problems:

| Problem                                   | What AWS PCA does                                                                                              |
| ----------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Certificates not trusted by other systems | PCA is a **central AWS-managed CA** â€” all AWS services (ALB, EC2, CloudFront, etc.) trust it                   |
| CA key exposed in cluster                 | PCAâ€™s private key is stored **inside AWS**, protected by HSM (Hardware Security Module) â€” **never leaves AWS** |
| No control / audit                        | AWS CloudTrail logs every issued cert                                                                          |
| No revocation                             | AWS PCA supports certificate revocation lists (CRL) and templates                                              |
